management of hyperkalemia

[!INFO]
Standard correction :

  • 10 Units of Insulin IV bolus +
    50ml of 50% dextrose.
  • Should cause a decrease of 1mEqL
  • but this is associated with hypoglycaemia in upto 19%.

Insulin should be given alone if the serum glucose is â‰¥250 mg/dL

[!NOTE] Avoiding hypoglycaemia

To avoid hypoglycemia, we recommend infusion of 10 percent dextrose at 50 to 75 mL/hour after the initial 25 g bolus and close monitoring of blood glucose levels every hour for five to six hours.

Insulin stimulates muscle Na/K ATPase which drives potassium into the muscle cells.

Insulin has this effect only at high concentrations which are achieved by IV boluses. The hypoglycaemic effect occurs at lower concentrations and therefore lasts longer.

Causes of increased CPK

CPK = CK.

creatine is a nitrogenous acid that is synthesised in the liver or ingested as dietary protein

creatine is transported to skeletal muscle and stored in the form of creatine phosphate, where it restores ATP after muscle contraction, before being converted to creatinine by non-enzymatic dehydration

Creatine Kinase (aka creatinine phosphokinase) is a catalyst for the formation of ATP from ADP via transfer of phosphate from creatine phosphate (which is an energy reservoir for muscle.

Urine cultures

Review of airway histology

Respiratory epithelium - ciliated pseudostratified columnar epithelium.


Note the presence of smooth muscle and it's decreasing thickness as the airways become smaller.

Bronchioles - intralobular airways < 1mm in diameter arising roughly after the 10th generation of branching.

Pathology

Bronchiectasis is the permanent dilation of bronchi and
bronchioles caused by destruction of the muscle and the
supporting elastic tissue, resulting from or associated with
chronic necrotizing infections. It is not a primary disease
but rather secondary to persisting infection or obstruction
caused by a variety of conditions

Once patients develop bronchiectasis, most commonly isolated organisms are haemophillus and pseudomonas and streptococcus pneumoniae.

Obstructive impairment (ie, reduced or normal FVC, low FEV1, and low FEV1/FVC) is the most frequent finding on spirometry. ;
$$
\LARGE{Obstruction = â†“\frac{FEV_{1}}{FVC}}
$$

See [[Lung function tests#Obstructive vs. restrictive diseases]]

Morphology

  • Usually affects bilateral lower lobes.
  • Permanent dilation -> â­small airways are traceable almost upto the pleura. (in normal lungs, they stop about 2 cm short of the pleura)
  • Chronic inflammatory exudate is seen.
  • Extensive desquamation of epithelium causing ulceration.
  • Healing is usually by fibrosis.
  • Abscesses can form as complications.

Diagnosis:

Clinical and CT:
CT features that are reliable signs of bronchiectasis:

  • Airway-to-arterial ratio â‰¥1.5 (internal airway lumen diameter/adjacent pulmonary artery diameter)
  • Lack of tapering of bronchi (tram track appearance)
  • Airway visibility within 1 cm of a costal pleural surface or touching the mediastinal pleura
  1. Haemoptysis
    [[#Causes of bronchiectasis and basis of disease]]
  2. Long term macrolides
    1. Studies show that long term macrolides can reduce exacerbation frequency.
    2. However, it can predispose to macrolide resistant non tuberculin mycobacteria infection so this has to be ruled out via culture before starting treatment. Source

Management of exacerbations

Control of acute bleeding with bronchoscopic local therapy or bronchial artery embolization.
Refractory disease: surgical therapy - ? resection

Epidemiology

Commoner in women.
Increases with age; marked increase after 60 years.

Causes of bronchiectasis and basis of disease

Common causes

Obstruction - tumour, lymph nodes, aspiration etc. <- impaired drainage
Inherited disorders -
Cystic fibrosis #autosomal-Recessive <- impaired clearance of mucous
Kartagener syndrome <- Ciliary impairement
Autosomal recessive #autosomal-Recessive
Situs inversus, chronic sinusitis, and bronchiectasis; Underlying pathology is primary ciliary diskinesia. Kartagener Xn is a subset of primary ciliary diskinesia (in which patients may not have situs inversus).
Screening test -> patients have low levels of nasal nitric oxide.

Immunoglobulin deficiencies <- recurrent infection
Necrotizing of suppurative pneumonia - staph aureus or klebsiella <- scarring and impaired clearance; ?exagerrated neutrophil response

Cystic fibrosis

  • #autosomal-Recessive ; requires two mutated copies of the CFTR gene involved in chloride and bicarbonate transport.
  • patients have thick secretions in lungs, GI tract, pancreas and reproductive tract.
  • Features: Chronic respiratory tract infections, including pseudomonas.
  • Males have obstructive azoospermia due to bilateral absence of vas deferens, allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, clubbing, pancreatic insufficiency, hypochloremic alkalosis, rectal prolapse and others.
  • Sperms express CFTR and spermatogenesis may be reduced.
  • Diagnosis: elevated sweat chloride, abnormal nasal potential difference.

Other causes

Young syndrome - similar to CF but no evidence of CF; rare diagnosis nowadays.
Associated with two rheumatic disorders - Sjogren syndrome and Rheumamtoid arthritis.
